06480nam a22009855i 9780813544625DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20082008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135446257 a10.36019/97808135446252doi  a(DE-B1597)530373  a(OCoLC)1058753708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBL71b.T49 2008eb (Online) 7aREL0000002bisacsh00aTheorizing Scriptures :bNew Critical Orientations to a Cultural Phenomenon /ced. by Vincent Wimbush. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (324 p.) :b33  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignifying on Scriptures0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistorically, religious scriptures are defined as holy texts that are considered to be beyond the abilities of the layperson to interpret. Their content is most frequently analyzed by clerics who do not question the underlying political or social implications of the text, but use the writing to convey messages to their congregations about how to live a holy existence. In Western society, moreover, what counts as scripture is generally confined to the Judeo-Christian Bible, leaving the voices of minorities, as well as the holy texts of faiths from Africa and Asia, for example, unheard. In this innovative collection of essays that aims to turn the traditional bible-study definition of scriptures on its head, Vincent L. Wimbush leads an in-depth look at the social, cultural, and racial meanings invested in these texts. Contributors hail from a wide array of academic fields and geographic locations and include such noted academics as Susan Harding, Elisabeth Shüssler Fiorenza, and William L. Andrews. Purposefully transgressing disciplinary boundaries, this ambitious book opens the door to different interpretations and critical orientations, and in doing so, allows an ultimately humanist definition of scriptures to emerge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aSacred booksxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aAndrews, William L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChireau, Yvonne P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Sathianathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCogdell DjeDje, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaldson, Laura E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGundaker, Grey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarding, Susan F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKassam, Tazim R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing-Hammond, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKort, Wesley A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Charles H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDannell, Colleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlajubu, Oyeronke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlivelle, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPage, Hugh R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabasa, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/